Part 2

By the winter of 2015, the name Punarjeevan was painted on the main wooden door in clean Bengali script.

The wood had stopped swelling.

Vikram had planed the edges himself, using a small steel block plane he'd bought from a hardware market in Shobhabazar.

The house had become clean, the bat droppings swept away, the courtyard tiles reset.

They had twenty-two beds now.

Sarita's fever came less often, but she had started using a walking stick. A simple bamboo cane, identical to the one Vikram had left in Odisha, except this one had no red cloth at the top.

Ananya was seventeen.

She had grown tall, her hair no longer in plates, but tied in a single ponytail with a thick rubber band.

She spent her mornings at the register table near the door, writing patient entries in a ledger that had a green cloth cover.

Her handwriting had become neat, the letters upright and small, just like the notes Vikram had written for her.

The courier arrived at twelve.

He didn't walk inside.

He stood at the threshold, his bicycle leaning against the wall, holding a yellow envelope.

"Vikram Ahuja?"

Vikram, who was clearing dead neem leaves from the courtyard drain, stood up.

"Yes."

"Registered post. From Cuttack. Forwarded from Bhubaneswar."

The postmarks on the yellow paper were overlapping, three circles of purple ink, one of them showing the date: *12-10-15.*

Vikram signed the slip.

The paper was cheap, rough to the touch, the yellow color slightly faded at the corners where the glue had dried.

He sat on the lowest step of the verandah.

Sarita was in the kitchen, the smell of boiling rice and cumin coming through the open window.

He tore the top of the envelope.

---

The letter was written on two sheets of ruled paper.

The handwriting was small, the letters rounded, with the specific, careful spacing he had seen on drafts of news articles ten years ago.

*Vikram,*

*I don't know if this address will find you. I asked Rohan's office three times before a clerk took pity on me and wrote the Kolkata post box number on a slip.*

*I am not writing to ask for forgiveness. Some things don't have a balance sheet.*

*After Odisha, Rajeev married me. He insisted on conversion. I did it because I had lost the paper job and had no other room to go to. He changed my name to Ummed.*

*It lasted four years.*

*The abuse was not loud. It was daily. He took the cards. He took the bank account. When our son was born, he said the child would have only one name, his.*

*Rehman.*

*Three years ago, Rajeev left. He went to Hyderabad with another reporter. He didn't leave a number or an address.*

*I raised Rehman alone. I work at a local press in Cuttack, proofreading municipal directories. It pays enough for the room and the rice, but nothing else.*

*Rehman is nineteen now. He has finished his intermediate. He doesn't want to work at the press. He wants to do service work. He wants to help people who have nothing.*

*I told him about you. Not the tycoon. The Vikram who walked away.*

*He wants to learn from you. He wants to work at your shelter.*

*If you can take him, guide him, it will give me some peace. A small payment against the debt I owe you.*

*He will arrive tomorrow. He has the Howrah passenger ticket.*

*Ira.*

---

Vikram sat there.

The neem leaves in the courtyard moved slightly in the wind, a dry, whispering sound against the stone.

Ummed.

The name was new, yet it had the cold weight of the transaction alert on his phone from Salt Lake.

*Rs. 340 debited.*

He looked at the yellow envelope.

The paper was cheap, the kind sold at railway station stalls for ten paise.

"Who was it?" Sarita asked, coming out of the kitchen with a plate of sliced cucumbers.

She sat on the step beside him.

"A letter," Vikram said.

"From Odisha?"

"From Ira."

Sarita didn't ask who Ira was.

Some names don't need a designation when you have lived with a man's silence for three years.

"What does she want?"

"Her son is coming tomorrow," Vikram said. "He wants to work here."

Sarita picked up a slice of cucumber.

"We have room," she said, looking at the courtyard well. "We always have room for someone who has nowhere else to go."

Vikram folded the paper.

He put it back into the yellow envelope.

The postmark was still purple, dry and clear under the grey light of the Bagbazar sky.

He kept it in his shirt pocket.

The cheap paper felt thin against his chest, but as he stood up to return to the drain, it had the weight of a stone that had finally found its well.

[End of Part 2]
